Dear Saravanan,

Thank you for completing the Section 13 IST review. I have gone through 
all ten responses carefully. Before addressing the content, two quick 
points on process.

First, on the Claude AI limit: I am arranging your Claude Pro 
subscription today. You should not have been running the IST review on 
the free tier. Going forward your session limit issue is resolved. 
Second, your commitment to not use ChatGPT for SPINRISE is noted and 
appreciated. The entire review chain must remain on Claude AI for 
consistency — your confirmation of this is the right professional response.

Now on the IST responses themselves.

*What is well answered and resolved*

*IST-5 through IST-8 are all clear and actionable. *Let me confirm what 
each one means for the FSD.

*IST-5 (Year-end):* No PO can be raised after financial year closure. 
Confirmed. SPINRISE must enforce this at the API layer — the 
ToValidFinYear check in RMIMod.bas becomes a server-side year boundary 
guard on every Create and Modify operation.

*IST-6 (Deletion guard):* This is a significant new business rule. PO 
cannot be deleted once the first level of approval has been completed. 
The VB6 code currently only blocks deletion when RM_Arrival records 
exist. Your answer adds a second guard that the current code does not 
have. Sasi, please add this as Step 0 in the Delete Guard sequence in 
FSD Section 5.10: check FIRST_APPFLG — if 'Y', hard stop with message 
'PO cannot be deleted after approval has commenced.' This is a SPINRISE 
improvement over the VB6 behaviour.

*IST-7 (Backdate): *No backdated PO entry in SPINRISE. Confirmed. The 
backdate flexibility in VB6 controlled by the in_para.backdate flag is 
not carried forward. PO date equals processing date only. Sasi, add this 
as a SPINRISE design decision in Section 12.

*IST-8 (Delete Reason): *DelReasonCode must be written to 
RM_Trans_Log.DelReason. This resolves Critical Defect CD-7. Sasi, update 
FSD Section 5.10 and Section 8.2 to record that the SPINRISE DELETE 
endpoint must write the selected delete reason to RM_Trans_Log.DelReason 
as part of the delete audit sequence.


*IST-4 — your most valuable response*

The nine support call patterns you have documented are exactly the kind 
of institutional knowledge the FSD process is designed to capture. Let 
me confirm what each one requires in the FSD:

*Points 1, 2, and 3 on GST: *GST rate percentage must be mandatory and 
must load from the Variety Master. For import transactions, GST 
applicability must be parameter-controlled and GST type must be selected 
manually based on that parameter. Supplier state validation must apply 
differently for Local, Interstate, and Import. These are new validations 
that must be added to FSD Section 4. *Sasi to add.*

*Points 4 and 8 on Arrival Type and UoM: *This is the most important 
data integrity finding. When a user selects Candy as the Rate Unit but 
the Arrival Type is KGS-wise, incorrect rate calculations result. 
SPINRISE must auto-default the Arrival Type based on the selected UoM: 
UoM = Candy defaults Arrival Type to Pack-wise; UoM = KGS defaults 
Arrival Type to KGS-wise. If the user changes one, the other should 
prompt or auto-correct. This must be in FSD Section 5 as a new auto-fill 
and consistency rule. *Sasi to add.*

*Points 5, 6, and 7 on UX:* Tab focus sequence, navigation, and lookup 
re-opening are known defects. These belong in the Critical Defects 
section of FSD Section 12. The lookup re-opening issue specifically — if 
a valid code is entered directly without using the lookup, the lookup 
window should not reopen — is a UX rule that must be documented in 
Section 2 for every lookup field.

*Point 9 on Common tax mode: *When tax calculation is set to 'Common for 
all varieties' and multiple varieties share one tax code, calculation 
errors occur. This must be documented as a validation in Section 4: when 
tax_choice = COMMON, verify that all line item tax codes are consistent 
before saving, and cross-check the calculated tax amount against the 
expected amount from the common tax rate.


*IST-3 — the print display rule is noted but the question was not answered*

Your response to IST-3 is valuable — PR Number and PR Date should 
display on the PO print only when the PO was raised against a PR. For 
direct or spot POs with no PR linkage, these fields should not appear. 
Sasi, this must be added to FSD Section 7 as a print business rule: the 
Crystal report must conditionally display PR No and PR Date based on 
whether iprno is populated.

However, the actual question was about SP_PRToPO_RMI and 
SP_PRToPO_RMIFilter — the stored procedures that handle the PR-to-PO 
conversion logic. *You have answered a print behaviour question, not the 
SP behaviour question.* The SP code has not been provided and the SP 
logic has not been submitted to Claude via Follow-up Prompt B.*This is 
still outstanding.* Please obtain both SP codes from SQL Server 
Management Studio and submit to Claude for Follow-up Prompt B analysis. 
The PR-to-PO conversion is the primary daily workflow for this screen 
and its SP logic must be in FSD Section 8 before the document can be 
approved.


*What still needs your clarification*

Four items from your responses need to be completed.

*IST-1 (RM_PARAM flags): *Your response is a policy statement, not an 
IST answer. What I need is: for each of the 8 RM_PARAM flags documented 
in FSD Section 11 (SuppLotNoReqArrival, CentralizedOrder, SeasoncalcReq, 
MasterEntryFlg, PRBased, PO_Approval, ADDTAXREQUIRED, ftamt), what is 
the current value at your major customer sites? Which flags are set 
differently from the documented SPINRISE defaults? Please provide a 
customer-wise breakdown or at minimum confirm which flags are 
universally set the same way and which ones vary. This is a one-time 
query you can run on any live customer database.

*IST-2 (Approval workflow):* The approver designations (RM Dept Head, 
Plant Head, Management) are useful. But three sub-questions remain 
unanswered. Which customers currently have PO_Approval = Y and run the 
3-level workflow? Which have 1 or 2 levels only? And which SCREEN or 
form handles the approval action itself in the current ERP? The FSD 
references POApproval() in RMIMod.bas but the screen where a user logs 
in to approve a PO is not documented anywhere.

*IST-9 (Cry_RMIPO_JAT_NEW):* If the layout and data are identical to 
Cry_RMI_PO_ALL, why was the report object renamed? The name suffix 
JAT_NEW suggests it was modified for a specific customer (JAT). Please 
physically open both RepRMI.rpt files and confirm they are the same 
file, or identify what differs. If identical, the FastReports migration 
can proceed from a single template inspection.

*IST-10 (With-Sample mode): *Which customer sites currently use 
wosample=Y? The SPINRISE default of N (Rate-Master mode) is confirmed. 
But the sites using wosample=Y need to be identified so the SPINRISE 
customer onboarding guide can flag this as a setup requirement for those 
specific customers.


*For Sasi — FSD update checklist from this IST review*

Sasi, please update the FSD with the following additions from this IST 
exchange before Saturday's meeting:

Section 4 — Add new validations: approval-based deletion block, GST 
mandatory from Variety Master, import GST parameter control, Arrival 
Type vs UoM consistency, Common tax mode cross-validation.

Section 5 — Add new business rules: UoM-to-ArrivalType auto-default 
(Candy to Pack-wise, KGS to KGS-wise), SPINRISE no-backdate design decision.

Section 5.10 Delete Guard — Add Step 0: FIRST_APPFLG check blocks 
deletion if Y.

Section 7 Print — Add conditional PR No and PR Date display rule: show 
only when iprno is populated.

Section 8.2 Delete Sequence — Update to confirm DelReasonCode write to 
RM_Trans_Log.DelReason as an explicit step.

Section 12 — Add UX defect items (tab focus, navigation, lookup re-open) 
as known defects to resolve in SPINRISE.

Once the two SPs are submitted to Claude and the SP analysis is in 
Section 8, and once Saravanan provides the four remaining IST answers, 
the FSD will be ready for TL-IST sign-off and the formal review chain.

*Good progress on this thread, Saravanan.* The IST-4 response in 
particular is the kind of knowledge transfer that makes this whole 
process worthwhile.

Regards,
T. Mani

