    <p>Dear Saravanan,<br>
      <br>
      Thank you for completing the Section 13 IST review. I have gone
      through all ten responses carefully. Before addressing the
      content, two quick points on process.<br>
      <br>
      First, on the Claude AI limit: I am arranging your Claude Pro
      subscription today. You should not have been running the IST
      review on the free tier. Going forward your session limit issue is
      resolved. Second, your commitment to not use ChatGPT for SPINRISE
      is noted and appreciated. The entire review chain must remain on
      Claude AI for consistency — your confirmation of this is the right
      professional response.<br>
      <br>
      Now on the IST responses themselves.<br>
      <br>
      <font size="4"><b>What is well answered and resolved</b></font><br>
      <br>
      <b>IST-5 through IST-8 are all clear and actionable. </b>Let me
      confirm what each one means for the FSD.<br>
      <br>
      <b>IST-5 (Year-end):</b> No PO can be raised after financial year
      closure. Confirmed. SPINRISE must enforce this at the API layer —
      the ToValidFinYear check in RMIMod.bas becomes a server-side year
      boundary guard on every Create and Modify operation.<br>
      <br>
      <b>IST-6 (Deletion guard):</b> This is a significant new business
      rule. PO cannot be deleted once the first level of approval has
      been completed. The VB6 code currently only blocks deletion when
      RM_Arrival records exist. Your answer adds a second guard that the
      current code does not have. Sasi, please add this as Step 0 in the
      Delete Guard sequence in FSD Section 5.10: check FIRST_APPFLG — if
      'Y', hard stop with message 'PO cannot be deleted after approval
      has commenced.' This is a SPINRISE improvement over the VB6
      behaviour.<br>
      <br>
      <b>IST-7 (Backdate): </b>No backdated PO entry in SPINRISE.
      Confirmed. The backdate flexibility in VB6 controlled by the
      in_para.backdate flag is not carried forward. PO date equals
      processing date only. Sasi, add this as a SPINRISE design decision
      in Section 12.<br>
      <br>
      <b>IST-8 (Delete Reason): </b>DelReasonCode must be written to
      RM_Trans_Log.DelReason. This resolves Critical Defect CD-7. Sasi,
      update FSD Section 5.10 and Section 8.2 to record that the
      SPINRISE DELETE endpoint must write the selected delete reason to
      RM_Trans_Log.DelReason as part of the delete audit sequence.<br>
      <br>
      <br>
      <b>IST-4 — your most valuable response</b><br>
      <br>
      The nine support call patterns you have documented are exactly the
      kind of institutional knowledge the FSD process is designed to
      capture. Let me confirm what each one requires in the FSD:<br>
      <br>
      <b>Points 1, 2, and 3 on GST: </b>GST rate percentage must be
      mandatory and must load from the Variety Master. For import
      transactions, GST applicability must be parameter-controlled and
      GST type must be selected manually based on that parameter.
      Supplier state validation must apply differently for Local,
      Interstate, and Import. These are new validations that must be
      added to FSD Section 4. <b>Sasi to add.</b><br>
      <br>
      <b>Points 4 and 8 on Arrival Type and UoM: </b>This is the most
      important data integrity finding. When a user selects Candy as the
      Rate Unit but the Arrival Type is KGS-wise, incorrect rate
      calculations result. SPINRISE must auto-default the Arrival Type
      based on the selected UoM: UoM = Candy defaults Arrival Type to
      Pack-wise; UoM = KGS defaults Arrival Type to KGS-wise. If the
      user changes one, the other should prompt or auto-correct. This
      must be in FSD Section 5 as a new auto-fill and consistency rule.
      <b>Sasi to add.</b><br>
      <br>
      <b>Points 5, 6, and 7 on UX:</b> Tab focus sequence, navigation,
      and lookup re-opening are known defects. These belong in the
      Critical Defects section of FSD Section 12. The lookup re-opening
      issue specifically — if a valid code is entered directly without
      using the lookup, the lookup window should not reopen — is a UX
      rule that must be documented in Section 2 for every lookup field.<br>
      <br>
      <b>Point 9 on Common tax mode: </b>When tax calculation is set to
      'Common for all varieties' and multiple varieties share one tax
      code, calculation errors occur. This must be documented as a
      validation in Section 4: when tax_choice = COMMON, verify that all
      line item tax codes are consistent before saving, and cross-check
      the calculated tax amount against the expected amount from the
      common tax rate.<br>
      <br>
      <br>
      <b>IST-3 — the print display rule is noted but the question was
        not answered</b><br>
      <br>
      Your response to IST-3 is valuable — PR Number and PR Date should
      display on the PO print only when the PO was raised against a PR.
      For direct or spot POs with no PR linkage, these fields should not
      appear. Sasi, this must be added to FSD Section 7 as a print
      business rule: the Crystal report must conditionally display PR No
      and PR Date based on whether iprno is populated.<br>
      <br>
      However, the actual question was about SP_PRToPO_RMI and
      SP_PRToPO_RMIFilter — the stored procedures that handle the
      PR-to-PO conversion logic. <b>You have answered a print behaviour
        question, not the SP behaviour question.</b> The SP code has not
      been provided and the SP logic has not been submitted to Claude
      via Follow-up Prompt B.<b> This is still outstanding.</b> Please
      obtain both SP codes from SQL Server Management Studio and submit
      to Claude for Follow-up Prompt B analysis. The PR-to-PO conversion
      is the primary daily workflow for this screen and its SP logic
      must be in FSD Section 8 before the document can be approved.<br>
      <br>
      <br>
      <font size="4"><b>What still needs your clarification</b></font><br>
      <br>
      Four items from your responses need to be completed.<br>
      <br>
      <b>IST-1 (RM_PARAM flags): </b>Your response is a policy
      statement, not an IST answer. What I need is: for each of the 8
      RM_PARAM flags documented in FSD Section 11 (SuppLotNoReqArrival,
      CentralizedOrder, SeasoncalcReq, MasterEntryFlg, PRBased,
      PO_Approval, ADDTAXREQUIRED, ftamt), what is the current value at
      your major customer sites? Which flags are set differently from
      the documented SPINRISE defaults? Please provide a customer-wise
      breakdown or at minimum confirm which flags are universally set
      the same way and which ones vary. This is a one-time query you can
      run on any live customer database.<br>
      <br>
      <b>IST-2 (Approval workflow):</b> The approver designations (RM
      Dept Head, Plant Head, Management) are useful. But three
      sub-questions remain unanswered. Which customers currently have
      PO_Approval = Y and run the 3-level workflow? Which have 1 or 2
      levels only? And which SCREEN or form handles the approval action
      itself in the current ERP? The FSD references POApproval() in
      RMIMod.bas but the screen where a user logs in to approve a PO is
      not documented anywhere.<br>
      <br>
      <b>IST-9 (Cry_RMIPO_JAT_NEW):</b> If the layout and data are
      identical to Cry_RMI_PO_ALL, why was the report object renamed?
      The name suffix JAT_NEW suggests it was modified for a specific
      customer (JAT). Please physically open both RepRMI.rpt files and
      confirm they are the same file, or identify what differs. If
      identical, the FastReports migration can proceed from a single
      template inspection.<br>
      <br>
      <b>IST-10 (With-Sample mode): </b>Which customer sites currently
      use wosample=Y? The SPINRISE default of N (Rate-Master mode) is
      confirmed. But the sites using wosample=Y need to be identified so
      the SPINRISE customer onboarding guide can flag this as a setup
      requirement for those specific customers.<br>
      <br>
      <br>
      <b>For Sasi — FSD update checklist from this IST review</b><br>
      <br>
      Sasi, please update the FSD with the following additions from this
      IST exchange before Saturday's meeting:<br>
      <br>
      Section 4 — Add new validations: approval-based deletion block,
      GST mandatory from Variety Master, import GST parameter control,
      Arrival Type vs UoM consistency, Common tax mode cross-validation.<br>
      <br>
      Section 5 — Add new business rules: UoM-to-ArrivalType
      auto-default (Candy to Pack-wise, KGS to KGS-wise), SPINRISE
      no-backdate design decision.<br>
      <br>
      Section 5.10 Delete Guard — Add Step 0: FIRST_APPFLG check blocks
      deletion if Y.<br>
      <br>
      Section 7 Print — Add conditional PR No and PR Date display rule:
      show only when iprno is populated.<br>
      <br>
      Section 8.2 Delete Sequence — Update to confirm DelReasonCode
      write to RM_Trans_Log.DelReason as an explicit step.<br>
      <br>
      Section 12 — Add UX defect items (tab focus, navigation, lookup
      re-open) as known defects to resolve in SPINRISE.<br>
      <br>
      Once the two SPs are submitted to Claude and the SP analysis is in
      Section 8, and once Saravanan provides the four remaining IST
      answers, the FSD will be ready for TL-IST sign-off and the formal
      review chain.<br>
      <br>
      <b>Good progress on this thread, Saravanan.</b> The IST-4 response
      in particular is the kind of knowledge transfer that makes this
      whole process worthwhile.<br>
      <br>
      Regards,<br>
      T. Mani<br>
      <br>
      cc: TL-IST Palanivel, TL-Dev Sasi (action items above)</p>
